\begin_layout Standard
To calculate the dynamics of a vortex with charge 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 in a more consistent way with the physical reality, which allows for the
 coupling between vortex core and the external dimensions of condensate,
 we could naïvely use a Thomas-Fermi (TF) Ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vi1"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi\left(\rho,\varphi,z,t\right)=A\left(t\right)\left[\frac{\rho^{2}}{\rho^{2}+\xi\left(t\right)^{2}}\right]^{\mathbf{\frac{\ell}{2}}}\sqrt{1-\frac{\rho^{2}}{R_{\rho}\left(t\right)^{2}}-\frac{z^{2}}{R_{z}\left(t\right)^{2}}}\exp\left[i\ell\varphi+iB_{\rho}\left(t\right)\frac{\rho^{2}}{2}+iB_{z}\left(t\right)\frac{z^{2}}{2}\right],\label{eq:TF-A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\series bold
where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\rho}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}(t)$
\end_inset

 are the condensate sizes in radial (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

) and axial (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

) directions, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(t)$
\end_inset

 is the size of vortex core.
 The variational parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\rho}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{z}(t)$
\end_inset

 specify the variations of the velocity field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathbf{v}=B_{\rho}(t)\rho\hat{\rho}+B_{z}(t)z\hat{z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
The next step is to
\series default
 calculate the equations of motion for the five variational parameters (
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\rho}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\rho}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{z}$
\end_inset

).
 Following these calculations, the equations of motion would be linearized.
 For the Ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TF-A"

\end_inset

, this procedure leads to imaginary frequencies which are not consistent
 with the stable configuration where a singly charged (
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=1$
\end_inset

) vortex resides at the center of the condensate.
 The linearized equations of motion can be written in a matrix form according
 to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M\ddot{\delta}+V\delta=0,\label{eq:2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the vector with components given by deviations of the variational parameters
 from their equilibrium values.
 The solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

 is a linear combination of oscillatory modes whose oscillation frequencies
 obey the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\prod_{n}\varpi_{n}^{2}=\det\left(M^{-1}V\right)=\frac{\det V}{\det M}.\label{eq:w2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to ensure that all frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi_{n}$
\end_inset

 are real, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det V/\det M>0$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det V>0$
\end_inset

 since its sign reflects the sign of the variational parameters which represents
 the external dimensions of the cloud in the stationary situation.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\det M$
\end_inset

 must also be positive.
 In the case of Ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TF-A"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=1$
\end_inset

, such conditions are not satisfied since 
\begin_inset Formula $\det M<0$
\end_inset

, which indicates that there is something wrong with Ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TF-A"

\end_inset

.
 In previous works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2-compvor,michele,sa-nomalmodes,rpteles1"

\end_inset

, since the authors did not consider the size of the vortex core as a variationa
l parameter, this problem did not appear.
 
\series bold
More specifically, the imaginary frequency problem arises for excitation
 modes where the vortex core and the external size of the cloud oscillate
 out of phase.
 This kind of motion generates a velocity field which changes the sign of
 its radial component as the distance to the vortex line is increased.
 Since the Ansatz (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TF-A"

\end_inset

) describes only linear variations of this component, it is natural to expect
 non-physical results in this case.
 
\end_layout

