\begin_layout Standard
We start with the Lagrangian density,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=\frac{i\hbar}{2}\left(\psi^{*}\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t}-\psi\frac{\partial\psi^{*}}{\partial t}\right)-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\left|\nabla\psi\right|^{2}-V\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\left|\psi\right|^{2}-\frac{g}{2}\left|\psi\right|^{4},\label{eq:2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
whose extremization leads to the Gross-Pitaevskii equation (GPE):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\hbar\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial t}=\left[-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla^{2}+V\left(\mathbf{r}\right)+g\left|\psi\right|^{2}\right]\psi,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\frac{1}{2}m\omega_{\rho}^{2}\left(\rho^{2}+\lambda^{2}z^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an external potential, the trap anisotropy is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\omega_{z}/\omega_{\rho}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the coupling constant.
 The complex field 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

 can be written as an amplitude profile multiplied by a respective phase,
 as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=f\left(w_{l},\mathbf{r}\right)e^{iS\left(\chi_{l},\mathbf{r}\right)},\label{eq:2-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left(\chi_{l},\mathbf{r}\right)=\ell\varphi+\sum_{l}\chi_{l}\phi_{l}(\mathbf{r}).\label{eq:2-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We denoted both, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{l}=w_{l}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{l}=\chi_{l}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, respectively, as the amplitude and phase variational parameters.
 In principle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi_{l}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 should be a complete set of functions but in our present approximation,
 we use only a representative incomplete set of functions.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2-2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2-3"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2-1"

\end_inset

, the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\int\mathcal{L}d^{3}\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=-\hbar\sum_{l}\dot{\chi_{l}}\int d^{3}\mathbf{r}f^{2}\phi_{l}-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\sum_{l}\chi_{l}^{2}\int d^{3}\mathbf{r}f^{2}\left|\nabla\phi_{l}\right|^{2}-\int d^{3}\mathbf{r}\left(\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\left|\nabla f\right|^{2}+Vf^{2}+\frac{g}{2}f^{4}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to account for the dynamics of all three variational parameters
 
\series bold
(
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\rho}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{z}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

)
\series default
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 we include a variational phase which also contains three variational parameters.
 This way we chose the following trial function: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S(\rho,z,t)=\ell\varphi+B_{\rho}(t)\frac{\rho^{2}}{2}+C(t)\frac{\rho^{4}}{4}+B_{z}(t)\frac{z^{2}}{2}.\label{eq:fase 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\series bold
This allows the radial component of the velocity field to change its sign
 for different distances to the symmetry axis of the cloud.

\series default
 As the superfluid current is connected to the density variation, it is
 also desirable that both, amplitude and phase, have the same number of
 variational parameters.
 
\series bold
It is worth noticing that, in principle, any other Ansatz allowing for such
 behavior of the velocity field would be equally valid.
 We chose to add an extra 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{4}$
\end_inset

 term to the wave-function phase due to its simplicity.

\series default
 The Ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fase 2"

\end_inset

 also leads to linearized equations of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\det M>0$
\end_inset

 which is consistent with the stability of the condensate with a singly
 charged vortex at its center.
\end_layout

