\begin_layout Standard
One of the mechanisms used for exciting collective modes is via modulation
 of the s-wave scattering length.
 This technique has been already applied to excite the lowest-lying quadrupole
 mode in a Lithium experiment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cm1"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we consider the time-dependent scattering length:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{s}(t)=a_{0}+\delta a\cos\left(\Omega t\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is equivalent to make 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rightarrow\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

, thus giving:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma(\tau)=\gamma_{0}+\delta\gamma\cos\left(\Omega\tau\right).\label{eq:slm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the average value of the interaction parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the modulation amplitude, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the excitation frequency.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:slm"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:3abc"

\end_inset

 and keeping only first-order terms (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\alpha$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\gamma$
\end_inset

), we obtain a nonhomogeneous linear equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M\ddot{\delta}+V\delta=P\cos\left(\Omega\tau\right)\label{eq:modulação}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=2\pi\delta\gamma\begin{pmatrix}\frac{2D_{7}}{r_{\rho0}^{3}r_{z0}}\\
\frac{D_{7}}{r_{\rho0}^{2}r_{z0}^{2}}\\
\frac{D_{7}^{\prime}}{r_{\rho0}^{2}r_{z0}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A particular solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:modulação"

\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{\gamma}\left(\tau\right)=\left(M^{-1}V-\Omega^{2}\right)^{-1}M^{-1}P\cos\left(\Omega\tau\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Projecting the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\gamma}\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 in the base 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{n}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $n=z,\rho,\xi$
\end_inset

) of the eigenvectors of the homogenous equation associated to Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:modulação"

\end_inset

, we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \delta_{n}|\delta_{\gamma}\left(\tau\right)\right\rangle =\frac{\left\langle \delta_{n}|M^{-1}P\right\rangle }{\varpi_{n}^{2}-\Omega^{2}}\cos\left(\Omega\tau\right).\label{eq:ngama}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since
\series bold
 the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle \delta_{n}|M^{-1}P\right\rangle \right|$
\end_inset

 is always positive
\series default
, it shows that specific collective modes can be excited using a scattering
 length modulation with small amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\gamma$
\end_inset

 and frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 close to one of the resonance frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig5"

\end_inset

, we see the results from a numerical solution of Eqs.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2d"

\end_inset

--
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2f"

\end_inset

 considering a time-dependent interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 according to Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:slm"

\end_inset

.
 There we can see the beat behavior corresponding to a superposition of
 the frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=6$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varpi_{\xi}=6.13$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

